{
  "text": "Small number of sportsmen who are not medically treated show how high is the dancers' awareness. They know, very well, the mechanisms of injuries and the significance of a swift introduction of rehabilitation (Wanke, Quarcoo, Uibel, Groneberg, 2012) . They also know which symptoms they should pay attention to and they understand that, in spite of the proper orthopaedic, traumatic or neurological treatment, the disregard of rehabilitation may lead to the disruption or the early end of their sport's career. Sportsmen's motivation to cure the injury is of twofold importance [CITATION_1] because their main goal is not to achieve a state from before the trauma but to achieve the ability of getting back to intensive training as quickly as possible. In ballroom dancing, apart from the public pressure, the strong incentive is the co-dancer, whom the injury burden affects the most. That is why they expect the fastest recovery of the strength and agility. The desire to get back on the floor results in reliable fulfilment of the doctor's instructions and physiotherapeutic suggestions. Nonetheless, physiotherapists and sports doctors should remember about the very detailed rehabilitation instructions for the sportsman, but mainly the gradual rehabilitation trainings, specifically accordingly to the trained discipline [CITATION_2] .",
  "citation_candidates": [
